## Current Limitation
In the current version of Mockito (3.11.2 at the time of writing), I'm not finding a good way to stub or verify overloaded methods.

Consider the following class:
```java
class Foo {

  int bar(boolean setting) { ... };
  int bar(boolean setting, int otherSetting) { ... };

}
```

If I wanted to stub an invocation of *either* `bar()` method, I currently have to stub *both* versions of the method independently.
Similarly, if I wanted to verify that *either* of the `bar()` methods had been called, I'd have to verify each one independently.

[This StackOverflow post](https://stackoverflow.com/q/46038220/14765128) illustrates the difficulty of finding a good workaround for this use case.

## Impact
- Tests become cluttered with multiple stubs/verifications, obscuring the primary purpose of the test.
- The removal of an overloaded method breaks all tests that stub/verify that method.
- The addition of an overloaded method creates the potential for uncaught errors in tests that stub/verify the existing overloaded methods.

## Possible Solutions
- Add an optional String parameter to the `when()` and `verify()` methods that will identify the overloaded method to stub/verify. 
     - As of yet I've never used Java's Reflection API, but a quick search inclines me to think this functionality could be powered by iterating through [Class.getDeclaredMethods()](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Class.html#i25) and checking each `Method` object's [getName()](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/reflect/Method.html#i11) to identify which methods should be stubbed.
```java
Foo mockFoo = mock(Foo.class);

// Proposed format
verify(mockFoo, never(), 'bar');  

// This would be equivalent to the following, but would still work 
// if `bar(String)` were added or `bar(boolean)` were removed.
verify(mockFoo, never()).bar(anyBoolean());
verify(mockFoo, never()).bar(anyBoolean(), anyInt());
```

- Create a version of an ArgumentMatcher that can match all versions of an overloaded method.
```java
Foo mockFoo = mock(Foo.class);

// Proposed format
when(mockFoo.bar(anyArgs()).thenReturn(42);   // `anyArgs()` returns the proposed ArgumentMatcher.

// This would be equivalent to the following, but would still work 
// if `bar(String)` were added or `bar(boolean)` were removed.
when(mockFoo.bar(anyBoolean())).thenReturn(42);
when(mockFoo.bar(anyBoolean(), anyInt())).thenReturn(42);
```

## Forseen Complications
- When stubbing overloaded methods with different return types, how would Mockito reconcile a valid value to return?
- The first "Possible Solution" can't be updated automatically when someone refactors a method name via his/her IDE.
- If using the first "Possible Solution", what happens if the given string doesn't match any method on the mock object?

